Redwine by David Havera

I will be evaluating a red wine quality dataset. This dataset contains over 1,599 red wines with 11 features consisting of the chemical properties of the wine. At least 3 wine experts rated the wine on a scale from 0 (bad) to 10 (excellent). I will be analyzing this data set to determine what chemical properties influence the quality of red wine.

What is the structure of your dataset?

There are 13 variables with 1,399 observations. All variables are numeric with the exception of X and quality being integers. There are no #N/A’s in the data set. I removed X from the dataset.

I created histograms for all the features and it looks like several of the variables are positively skewed. I will dig deeper into this once I select the features of interest but it’s good to know this set could benefit from log scaling.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

I decided on the following features of interest based on the highest correlation to quality: alcohol, volatile acidity, and sulphates.

Alcohol has a positive correlation to quality of 0.48 and over 75% of the wines have at least 11% alcohol. It appears anything above 13 and below 8 would be an outlier.

Sulphates have a .25 correlation to quality and over 75% of the wines have at least a 0.75 level of sulphates. It appears anything above 1 and below 0.25 would be an outlier.

Volatile acidity has a (.39) correlation to quality and over 75% of the wines have at least a 0.6 level of acidity. It appears anything above 1 and below 0.1 would be an outlier.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of
looking at your feature(s) of interest?

I chose the variables with the higest correlation to quality: alcohol, volatile.acidity, and sulphates. I ran the R2 for these features against quality and came up with a total R2 of 0.44, which means that 44% of quality can be explained by these variables.
Sulphates looks particularly low at only 6%.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features
(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

I found it interesting that fixed acidity had a correlation of 0.67 to citric acid. There seems to be a lot of features related to acid in the dataset. If I am not able to accurately predict from the three features that I chose, then I will look into engineering another feature around acidity that combines citric acid.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The strongest relationship was 0.48 correlation of quality to alcohol.
I expect that this is the most impactful feature to predict the quality of wine, but we will later test this hypothesis.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of
looking at your feature(s) of interest?

Per the graph below, density has a strong negative correlation to alcohol of (0.5) and a positive correlation of 0.36 to residual sugars.
This makes sense since the data set description of this feature says that density is dependent on alcohol levels and sugars.
However, it’s interesting to see the relationship in terms of correlation numbers.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

Earlier I could have said that residual sugars is a throw away variable because it has only 0.0137 correlation to quality. However, residual sugar can impact density which can negativitly impact alcohol which can impact wine quality. I wonder if PCA would condense residual sugars, density, and alcohol together. I also believe that removing the outliers from residual sugar would change this chart significantly.

OPTIONAL: Did you create any models with your dataset? Discuss the
strengths and limitations of your model.

I chose the random forest (RF) to evaluate the dataset.

Strengths of RF: + Limited parameter tuning … default parameters often have great performance + Fast + Versitile + Great for feature selection because it evaluates a lot of decision tree variations + Illustrates information gain by inclusion/exclusion of variables in the forest

Limitations of RF: + Poor Peformance: small data sets + Fragmentation Problem: each split has diminishing information gain + Prone to overfitting

The random forest classifier is a powerful tool to predict the quality of wine.

It’s good to see this classifier confirms that alcohol (the feature with the highest correlation) is indeed the most important for predicting quality.

The correlation map is a great visual to show why we initially chose alcohol, volatile.acidity, and sulphates as the main features to explore.
It also highlights the relationships we observed between other features such as density and residual sugars and alcohol. I would use this to further explore additional features to test in the decision tree.

PCA doesn’t provide a clear view on components, so further analysis is needed to determine how features would be condensed into components. However, it appears from this graph that there could be two components (0,0) and (0,1)

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

This graph is a great illustration that shows the impact of feature scaling alcohol. The initial histogram of alcohol was very spread out and difficult to read, but log transforming the data gives us a much cleaner look at this feature.

Plot Two

Description Two

I chose the graph above because I wanted to further investigate the relationship between residual sugars and density. There does still appear to be a direct linear relationship between these variables even after removing outliers.

Plot Three

Description Three

I added the feature names to my PCA graph and found there were 4 components. I found it fascinating that alcohol, sulphates and volatile acidity all belonged to seperate components. This makes me believe that these features selected are fairly balanced. However, PH belongs to a seperate component and perhaps adding this feature would have increased the performance of the classifier.

Reflection

I analyzed the data and built a model that could correclty predict the wine quality with a high accuracy based on alcohol content, sulphates, and volatile acidity.

I do believe that accuracy can be further improved because the 3 features of interest only explained 35% of the variance, so my next step would be to run the model with the 4 PCA components that we discovered in final plot 3. Feature selection and feature engineering are areas that I struggled with. I took a trial and error approach by only selecting the 3 highest features with a correlation to quality. However, an additional next step would be to use a pipeline of PCA, SelectKBest, and the random forest classifier to put together a more scientific approach to feature selection.

Overall, I am happy to have successfully built a base level starting point upon which more indepth analysis can be performed.
